{
  "Where does most gas exchange between the atmosphere and ocean occur?": "",
  "In underwater caves": "",
  "At hydrothermal vents": "",
  "At the deep ocean floor": "",
  "At the ocean surface": "",
  "Gas exchange between the atmosphere and ocean primarily occurs at the ocean surface, where air and water are in direct contact. Wind and waves increase the surface area, promoting more efficient gas transfer.": "",
  "How does water temperature affect the solubility of oxygen in seawater?": "",
  "Only tropical water can dissolve oxygen": "",
  "Warmer water holds more dissolved oxygen": "",
  "Temperature has no effect on oxygen solubility": "",
  "Colder water holds more dissolved oxygen": "",
  "Cold water can hold more dissolved oxygen than warm water because gas molecules move more slowly at lower temperatures and are more easily retained in the liquid. This is why polar waters tend to be more oxygen-rich than tropical waters.": "",
  "What is the primary biological source of dissolved oxygen in the ocean?": "",
  "Respiration by fish": "",
  "Photosynthesis by phytoplankton and marine plants": "",
  "Chemical reactions with sea salts": "",
  "Decomposition of organic matter": "",
  "Photosynthesis by phytoplankton and other marine plants produces the majority of dissolved oxygen in the ocean. These organisms use sunlight and CO₂ to make organic compounds, releasing O₂ as a byproduct.": "",
  "Which process removes dissolved oxygen from seawater?": "",
  "Photosynthesis": "",
  "Evaporation of water": "",
  "Freezing of sea ice": "",
  "Respiration by marine organisms": "",
  "Aerobic respiration by marine organisms, from bacteria to whales, consumes dissolved oxygen. Decomposition of dead organic matter by bacteria also uses large amounts of oxygen, particularly in deeper waters.": "",
  "What happens to carbon dioxide when it dissolves in seawater?": "",
  "It remains as dissolved CO₂ gas only": "",
  "It reacts with water to form carbonic acid, bicarbonate, and carbonate ions": "",
  "It bonds with sodium chloride": "",
  "It immediately escapes back into the atmosphere": "",
  "When CO₂ dissolves in seawater, it reacts with water to form carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), which then dissociates into bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) and carbonate (CO₃²⁻) ions. This series of reactions is central to the ocean's carbon chemistry.": "",
  "Which zone of the ocean typically has the highest concentration of dissolved oxygen?": "",
  "The abyssal zone": "",
  "The surface mixed layer": "",
  "The hadal zone": "",
  "The oxygen minimum zone": "",
  "The surface mixed layer has the highest dissolved oxygen because it is in direct contact with the atmosphere and receives oxygen from photosynthesis. Wind and wave action help mix oxygen into this layer.": "",
  "What role does wind play in ocean gas exchange?": "",
  "Wind removes all gases from the ocean surface": "",
  "Wind increases gas exchange by creating waves and turbulence at the surface": "",
  "Wind has no effect on gas exchange": "",
  "Wind only affects temperature, not gas exchange": "",
  "Wind increases gas exchange by generating waves and turbulence that break the ocean's surface layer, increasing the area of air-water contact. Higher wind speeds lead to greater rates of gas transfer between the atmosphere and ocean.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of global oxygen production comes from marine photosynthesis?": "",
  "About 90%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 25%": "",
  "About 50% or more": "",
  "Marine photosynthesis, primarily by phytoplankton, produces approximately 50% or more of the world's oxygen. This makes the ocean one of the most important sources of atmospheric oxygen on Earth.": "",
  "How does salinity affect the solubility of gases in seawater?": "",
  "Salinity only affects CO₂ solubility, not O₂": "",
  "Higher salinity decreases gas solubility": "",
  "Higher salinity increases gas solubility": "",
  "Salinity has no effect on gas solubility": "",
  "Higher salinity decreases the solubility of gases in water due to the \"salting out\" effect. Dissolved ions occupy space and interact with water molecules, reducing the water's capacity to hold dissolved gases like O₂ and CO₂.": "",
  "What is the ocean's biological pump?": "",
  "The circulation of warm water to the poles": "",
  "The process by which surface organisms fix carbon and transport it to the deep ocean": "",
  "The release of oxygen from hydrothermal vents": "",
  "A machine used by scientists to sample deep water": "",
  "The biological pump is the process by which phytoplankton fix CO₂ through photosynthesis and the resulting organic carbon is transported to deeper waters when organisms die, sink, or are consumed. This moves carbon from the surface to the deep ocean.": "",
  "What does \"gas solubility\" mean?": "",
  "The speed at which gas escapes from water": "",
  "The maximum amount of a gas that can dissolve in a given volume of liquid under specific conditions": "",
  "The rate at which gas bubbles rise through water": "",
  "The temperature at which a gas becomes liquid": "",
  "Gas solubility is the maximum concentration of a gas that can dissolve in a liquid at a given temperature, pressure, and salinity. It determines how much O₂ or CO₂ seawater can hold under specific environmental conditions.": "",
  "What is the \"oxygen minimum zone\" (OMZ)?": "",
  "The deepest part of the ocean where no oxygen exists": "",
  "A surface layer where photosynthesis produces maximum oxygen": "",
  "A mid-depth layer where dissolved oxygen is at its lowest due to respiration and decomposition": "",
  "An artificial zone created by pollution": "",
  "The oxygen minimum zone (OMZ) is a layer typically found between 200–1000 meters depth where dissolved oxygen concentrations are at their lowest. This occurs because respiration and decomposition consume oxygen, while distance from the surface limits replenishment.": "",
  "What is \"Henry's Law\" as it applies to ocean gas exchange?": "",
  "Gases always move from the ocean to the atmosphere": "",
  "The amount of gas that dissolves in a liquid is proportional to the partial pressure of that gas above the liquid": "",
  "Temperature does not affect gas dissolution": "",
  "The rate of gas exchange is independent of wind speed": "",
  "Henry's Law states that at a constant temperature, the amount of gas dissolved in a liquid is directly proportional to the partial pressure of that gas in the atmosphere above the liquid. Higher atmospheric CO₂ levels therefore lead to more CO₂ dissolving in the ocean.": "",
  "What does \"partial pressure\" of a gas mean?": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a single gas in a mixture of gases": "",
  "The reduction of pressure during a storm": "",
  "The total atmospheric pressure at sea level": "",
  "The pressure at a certain depth underwater": "",
  "Partial pressure is the pressure contribution of an individual gas in a mixture of gases. For example, the partial pressure of CO₂ (pCO₂) in the atmosphere determines how much CO₂ will dissolve into the ocean surface.": "",
  "What is \"diffusion\" in the context of gas exchange?": "",
  "The sinking of cold water to the ocean floor": "",
  "The process of water evaporating from the ocean": "",
  "The reflection of sunlight off the ocean surface": "",
  "The movement of gas molecules from an area of higher concentration to lower concentration": "",
  "Diffusion is the net movement of molecules from a region of higher concentration to a region of lower concentration. In ocean gas exchange, if the surface water has less dissolved CO₂ than the atmosphere, CO₂ will diffuse from air into the water.": "",
  "What is \"respiration\" in the marine environment?": "",
  "The evaporation of water from the ocean surface": "",
  "The process by which organisms use oxygen and produce carbon dioxide to release energy from food": "",
  "The absorption of sunlight by algae": "",
  "The formation of ocean currents": "",
  "Respiration is a metabolic process where organisms consume oxygen and organic compounds to produce energy, releasing CO₂ and water as byproducts. In the ocean, respiration by all marine life forms is a major consumer of dissolved oxygen.": "",
  "What does the term \"carbon sink\" refer to?": "",
  "A region that releases more carbon than it absorbs": "",
  "A measurement of ocean salinity": "",
  "A type of deep sea trench": "",
  "A natural reservoir that absorbs and stores more carbon than it releases": "",
  "A carbon sink is a natural system that absorbs more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than it releases. The ocean is the largest active carbon sink on Earth, absorbing roughly 25-30% of human-produced CO₂ annually.": "",
  "What is \"supersaturation\" of a dissolved gas?": "",
  "When the concentration of dissolved gas is below equilibrium": "",
  "When a gas is completely absent from water": "",
  "When the concentration of dissolved gas exceeds the equilibrium value for current conditions": "",
  "When gas cannot dissolve due to high salinity": "",
  "Supersaturation occurs when the dissolved gas concentration exceeds what the water can hold at equilibrium under current temperature and pressure conditions. This can happen when water warms rapidly or during intense photosynthesis, and excess gas tends to escape to the atmosphere.": "",
  "What does the term \"ventilation\" mean in physical oceanography?": "",
  "The process by which surface water carrying dissolved gases sinks and supplies oxygen to deeper layers": "",
  "The mixing of fresh and salt water in estuaries": "",
  "The creation of tidal pools": "",
  "The warming of surface water by solar radiation": "",
  "Ventilation in oceanography refers to the process by which surface water, enriched with atmospheric gases, is transported to the ocean interior through sinking or mixing. This is the primary way deep ocean waters receive dissolved oxygen.": "",
  "What is \"equilibrium\" in the context of air-sea gas exchange?": "",
  "The point at which all gas has escaped from the water": "",
  "When waves and wind completely stop": "",
  "When the rate of gas dissolving into water equals the rate of gas escaping to the atmosphere": "",
  "When ocean temperature equals atmospheric temperature": "",
  "Equilibrium in air-sea gas exchange occurs when the flux of gas molecules entering the water equals the flux leaving it, resulting in no net transfer. At equilibrium, the dissolved gas concentration is determined by the gas's partial pressure and solubility.": "",
  "A marine biologist observes a massive phytoplankton bloom in a bay. How would this bloom most likely affect dissolved oxygen levels during the daytime?": "",
  "Dissolved oxygen would remain unaffected": "",
  "Dissolved oxygen would be converted to nitrogen": "",
  "Dissolved oxygen would increase due to photosynthesis": "",
  "Dissolved oxygen would decrease significantly": "",
  "During the day, a large phytoplankton bloom carries out intense photosynthesis, producing substantial amounts of dissolved oxygen. The water can even become supersaturated with oxygen. However, at night when photosynthesis stops, respiration can cause oxygen to drop significantly.": "",
  "A scientist finds that a deep ocean basin has almost no dissolved oxygen. What is the most likely cause?": "",
  "Too much photosynthesis is occurring at depth": "",
  "The water is too cold to hold dissolved oxygen": "",
  "Wind is mixing oxygen out of the deep water": "",
  "Bacterial decomposition of sinking organic matter has consumed the available oxygen": "",
  "In poorly ventilated deep basins, bacteria decompose sinking organic matter (dead organisms, fecal pellets) through respiration, consuming dissolved oxygen. Without adequate mixing or circulation to replenish oxygen from the surface, the water becomes anoxic.": "",
  "Atmospheric CO₂ levels have risen from 280 ppm to over 420 ppm since the Industrial Revolution. According to Henry's Law, how has this affected the ocean?": "",
  "The ocean has absorbed less CO₂ because warmer temperatures decrease solubility": "",
  "The ocean's CO₂ content is independent of atmospheric levels": "",
  "The ocean has absorbed more CO₂ because higher atmospheric pCO₂ increases dissolution": "",
  "The ocean has released CO₂ in response to rising atmospheric levels": "",
  "According to Henry's Law, increasing the partial pressure of CO₂ in the atmosphere increases the amount that dissolves in the ocean surface. The ocean has absorbed roughly 30% of anthropogenic CO₂ emissions, leading to measurable changes in ocean chemistry.": "",
  "A coastal region experiences upwelling, bringing deep, cold water to the surface. What would you predict about dissolved CO₂ in the upwelled water?": "",
  "Upwelling has no effect on CO₂ concentrations": "",
  "It would contain very little dissolved CO₂": "",
  "It would be rich in dissolved CO₂ from deep-water respiration and decomposition": "",
  "It would contain only dissolved oxygen": "",
  "Deep ocean water accumulates CO₂ from the respiration and decomposition of organic matter over time. When this water is brought to the surface through upwelling, it carries elevated dissolved CO₂ levels, which can be released to the atmosphere.": "",
  "A fish farmer notices large fish die-offs in a warm, stagnant pond during summer. What is the most likely cause?": "",
  "Low dissolved oxygen due to warm temperatures and high biological oxygen demand": "",
  "The water became too saline for the fish": "",
  "Too much sunlight damaged the fish directly": "",
  "Excessive dissolved oxygen poisoned the fish": "",
  "Warm water holds less dissolved oxygen, and stagnant water has little circulation to replenish oxygen from the atmosphere. Combined with high respiration rates from bacteria and other organisms in summer, dissolved oxygen can drop to lethal levels for fish.": "",
  "During a storm, large waves crash along the coast. How does this event affect gas exchange?": "",
  "Gas exchange decreases because the water is disturbed": "",
  "Only CO₂ exchange is affected, not O₂": "",
  "Gas exchange stops completely during storms": "",
  "Gas exchange increases because wave action and bubbles increase air-water contact": "",
  "Storms significantly increase gas exchange rates. Breaking waves inject air bubbles below the surface and create spray above, both of which dramatically increase the surface area for air-water contact and enhance dissolution of atmospheric gases.": "",
  "A limnologist compares gas exchange in a freshwater lake and a nearby ocean bay with similar temperatures. Which body of water would hold more dissolved oxygen?": "",
  "The freshwater lake because lower salinity allows greater gas solubility": "",
  "The ocean bay because salt enhances oxygen solubility": "",
  "Neither can hold dissolved oxygen at the same temperature": "",
  "Both would hold the same amount": "",
  "At the same temperature, freshwater can hold more dissolved oxygen than saltwater due to the salting-out effect. Dissolved ions in seawater reduce the water's capacity to dissolve gases, meaning the freshwater lake would have higher oxygen solubility.": "",
  "A research vessel measures high pCO₂ in surface water at a tropical upwelling zone. What will likely happen to the CO₂?": "",
  "It will sink to the deep ocean": "",
  "It will be immediately converted to oxygen": "",
  "It will be absorbed by nearby land plants": "",
  "The excess CO₂ will degas from the ocean surface into the atmosphere": "",
  "When surface ocean water has a higher pCO₂ than the atmosphere, the gas flux is from sea to air—the ocean releases CO₂. Upwelling zones are often sources of CO₂ to the atmosphere because the upwelled deep water is enriched in CO₂.": "",
  "If global warming causes ocean surface temperatures to rise by 2°C, what combined effect would this have on dissolved oxygen and CO₂?": "",
  "Temperature has no effect on gas solubility": "",
  "Both dissolved O₂ and CO₂ solubility would increase": "",
  "Both dissolved O₂ and CO₂ solubility would decrease": "",
  "O₂ solubility would increase while CO₂ solubility decreases": "",
  "Warmer water has reduced solubility for all gases. A 2°C rise in ocean surface temperature would decrease the capacity of seawater to hold both dissolved oxygen and CO₂. This creates a positive feedback loop where the warming ocean absorbs less CO₂ and holds less O₂.": "",
  "A coral reef is located in warm, shallow water near a nutrient-rich runoff area. The reef experiences nighttime oxygen crashes. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Corals produce excess oxygen at night": "",
  "Nutrient runoff fuels algal growth whose nighttime respiration depletes oxygen in warm water with already low O₂ capacity": "",
  "The reef consumes oxygen to build its limestone skeleton": "",
  "Only daytime light can affect dissolved gas levels": "",
  "Nutrient-rich runoff promotes algal blooms. During the day, algae produce oxygen via photosynthesis, but at night, all organisms respire without photosynthetic oxygen production. In warm water with reduced O₂ capacity, this can lead to dangerously low oxygen levels.": ""
}